The Hague Parliament Building, Netherlands Photo: ICTheir name: "Immediate Clarity Brigade." Their mission: Help lead Dutch civil servants out of the maze of bureaucratic jargon that is bamboozling ordinary people.Some than 100 coaches will help government administrators write clearer letters to citizens and website announcements, authorities said on Wednesday. The government said there will be "language coaches in all corners of the country, training courses to teach officials to write more clearly and practical tools to improve communication with people."The interior ministry said in a statement there would be 100 language coaches, experts and "ambassadors" by 2020. "We want to make sure that people can get involved and immediately understand the mail they receive from authorities," Secretary of State Raymond Knops said.Legal jargon has also been criticized for being too complicated. In August 2018, a minister said the language used by judges to hand out sentences was incomprehensible for some citizens. 
